Results. To test eq 5, we compared its values for ,G using t = 78.3 for a series of small-molecule solutes with those from free energy perturbation (FEP) calc~lations.~In the FEP calculations: the perturbations consisted of electrically charging and discharging the solutes in a bath of TIP4P water molecules. Except for hydrogen radii, the same nonbonded parameters (atomic charges and radii) were used in both the FEP and eq 5 calculations, and these were taken from the OPLS force field.6 The results are given in Table I. Taking the G, data for neutral molecules, we found a linear correlation (slope = 1.1, correlation
coefficient 9 = 0.98) between the results of FEP and eq 5.
Although FEP on NH4+and AcO- gives G@ more negative than does eq 5, the FEP values are also more negative than experimental G,, by 10-20 kcal/mol. Thus G I has similar values for small molecules whether calculated by &P using an explicit, molecular solvent or by our continuum model.
In Table 1 we also compare total solvation energies (Gd)found by experiment with those from eqs 2 and 5. Here too the correlation is linear (slope = 0.96, r2 = 0.96). The correlation is
- illustrated in Figure 1, which plots the neutral molecule G,, data
from Table I . Even for ions, the model performs well and gives aqueous I M NH,OAc as dissociated in spite of the 130 kcal/mol attraction between the ions in vacuo. G,, is sensitive to the partial charges used. For example, only a 10% reduction
in the OPLS charges of MeSH was required to lower ,G by -0.9 kcal/mol and bring G,, to within 1.2 kcal/mol of experiment.
Thus solvation free energies are calculated reliably only when accurate atomic partial charges are used.
